In this section, you can learn how to create a MongoDB Search index on the `monthlyPhoneTransactions`
collection.

Create a `CreateIndex.java` file in your `search-materialized-view` project directory,
and copy and paste the following code into this file.

```java
import com.mongodb.client.*;
import org.bson.Document;

public class CreateIndexExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Replace the connection string with your MongoDB deployment's connection string
        String connectionString = "<connection-string>";

        try (MongoClient mongoClient = MongoClients.create(connectionString)) {
            MongoDatabase database = mongoClient.getDatabase("sample_supplies");
            MongoCollection<Document> collection = database.getCollection("monthlyPhoneTransactions");
            String indexName = "monthlySalesIndex";

            // Create the MongoDB Search index definition for the document field
            Document searchIdx = new Document(
                    "mappings",
                    new Document("dynamic", true)
            );
            collection.createSearchIndex(indexName, searchIdx);
            System.out.println("New index name: " + indexName);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("Error creating Atlas Search index: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

```

Replace `<connection-string>` with the connection string for your
Atlas cluster or local Atlas deployment.

Atlas Cluster

Your connection string should use the following format:

```
mongodb+srv://<db_username>:<db_password>@<clusterName>.<hostname>.mongodb.net
```

To learn more, see [Driver](connect-via-driver).

Local or Self-Managed

Your connection string should use the
following format:

```
mongodb://localhost:<port-number>/?directConnection=true
```

To learn more, see [Connection Strings](manual/reference/connection-string).

Compile and run your application in your IDE or your shell.

**Input:**

```shell
javac CreateIndex.java
java CreateIndex
```

**Output:**

```
New index name: monthlySalesIndex
```

